<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence to Environmental Audit Committee inquiry into DEFRA consultation on Biodiversity Offsetting in England</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Michael </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Hannis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and Sian Sullivan</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Biodiversity offsetting (BO) is presented as a win-win solution reconciling increased development with a net gain for biodiversity. This framing is inaccurate, ideologically driven, and risks distracting policy-makers and practitioners from genuine core concerns of biodiversity conservation policy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is a substantial risk of BO policy being influenced by vested interests with privileged access to Government.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 23pt; padding-left:13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The proposed offsetting metric incorporates problematic spatial and temporal assumptions which contradict established ecological principles.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Authors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Michael </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Hannis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is an AHRC-funded Postdoctoral Researcher in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Geography, Environment and Development Studies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">department at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Birkbeck</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> College, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">University of London.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Sian Sullivan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is Senior Lecturer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in Environment and Development, department of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Geography, Environment and Development Studies, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Birkbeck</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> College, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">University of London, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and a Co-Investigator for the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Leverhulme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Centre for the Study of Value</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. (</span><a href="http://www.sed.manchester.ac.uk/research/LCSV/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">www.sed.manchester.ac.uk/research/LCSV/</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">writing jointly but in a personal capacity, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this submission does not represent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the view</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Birkbeck</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">College </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">any other body</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We submit this evidence in order to enable the Committee to consider information and insights gained through ongoing academic research, some of which is as yet unpublished. This includes Sian Sullivan’s supervision of current PhD research into the unfolding of the DEFRA offsets pilots and policy, conducted as part of a studentship funded by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Leverhulme</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Trust.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are preparing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a response to the DEFRA consultation addressing the specific questions asked therein, but since the focus of that consultation is firmly on operational details, we welcome this opportunity to make representations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on some of the wider issues raised by the proposed introduction of Biodiversity Offsetting (hereafter BO).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We request that the Committee consider as part of this evidence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">our</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">short report </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Offsetting Nature?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Habitat Banking and Biodiversity Offsets in the English Land Use Planning System</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which explains our perspective on BO in more detail.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Proceeding from an analysis of DEFRA’s proposals and the bac</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">kground to them, we argue in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Offsetting Nature? </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">displacing and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">marketising</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the mitigation of habitat degradation is likely to undermine place-based connections and entrench the separation between human and non-human</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. For this and other reasons BO is likely to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> retard rather than facilitate the emergence of ecologically sustainable human settlements. We also note </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that the promotion of BO is widely </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">characterised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by an ideological conviction that it is possible to achieve a “win-win” outcome, even in the absence of any significant evidence to support this conviction. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Green Paper and its associated consultation process illustrate and substantiate these concerns. Our referenced comments on the Green Paper will be laid out in our consultation response, but the consultation process is itself also problematic. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For example, our experience of a recent DEFRA workshop held as part of the consultation (at Nobel House, London on 27</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Sept. 2013) underlined our concern that BO is being embraced primarily as a way to “unblock” development, by making this not only easier but also more profitable. The Head of DEFRA’s Major Infrastructure and Environment Unit set the tone in his opening remarks, explaining that BO had the potential to make the mitigation of development impacts “quicker, simpler, cheaper, more certain, and more strategic”.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The underlying assumptions firstly that more development is needed, and secondly that the “regulatory burden” of complying with planning and environmental legislation does in fact constitute a significant blockage to development, remain unexamined. Clearly the former is a contested and ideologically charged assertion, which also raises the broader question of whether biodiversity conservation policy should aim to facilitate development.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s for the latter, it is our understanding that this assumption has been substantially undermined by DEFRA’s own research.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Developers and others at the workshop confirmed that, just as suggested in our report (on p14), the achievement of increases in net developable area by means of offsetting would be very attractive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, particularly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">housebuilders</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and could in some cases easily cover the cost of the required offsets, thus making housing development more profitable. This increased profitability goes some way to explaining the enthusiasm shown for BO by some developers, but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is clearly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not a legitimate objective for biodiversity conservation policy.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There are however other interest groups seeking commercial gain as players in offsets markets, but as intermediaries, brokers and ‘habitat bank managers’ rather than as developers. The influence of such companies on policy-making appears to be substantial, though not always immediately evident. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> major reason for this is that key individuals within them also hold influential positions as consultants and advisors to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on BO policy. One is even deputy chair of the body charged with providing quality assurance for the offsetting pilots</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (see </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Offsetting Nature?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, p5)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This dynamic was well illustrated at the same DEFRA workshop referred to above. At this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> event</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, one highly articulate and expert participant lost no opportunity, whether in breakout groups or in plenary discussion, to promote at length his view that BO should be introduced without delay as it would be of great benefit to the national economy: it should be mandatory rather than voluntary, and should be structured in such a way as to encourage the development of a “competitive market” in offsets. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This individual identified himself as a lead author of the influential </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ecosystem Markets Task Force report, which drew broadly these same conclusions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and is explicitly acknowledged in the ministerial Foreword as a major influence on the Green Paper. He did not however mention that he is also “Director Europe for The Environment Bank Ltd, a company at the forefront of emerging UK and EU ecosystems markets”.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Environment Bank is a commercial company with a clear vested interest in the expansion, outsourcing and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">commercialisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of BO. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Described as an independ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ent broker for the delivery of “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mitigation and compensation schemes asso</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ciated with planned development”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has teamed with a US </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">company</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">Mission </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">Markets</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super">TM</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal">,</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">create an online conservation credit trading platform, hosted in the US, for the buying and selling of UK conservation credits, particularly biodiversity offsets.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Yet the Environment Bank’s staff are intimately involved in the administration of DEFRA’s evaluative BO pilot schemes (particularly in Essex and Warwickshire), in the quality control of these pilots (via Natural England), and in writing reports for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (via the EMTF) arguing that BO should be rolled out further and faster.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We would urge both the Committee and DEFRA to consider carefully whether such blurring of roles best serves the interests of balanced and impartial policy-making. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is however not only an issue in relation to the pilots. A situation appears to be developing in which one such brokerage company might advise the developer, the planning authority and the offset provider in a given case, before then becoming responsible for assuring the long-term delivery of the promised offset. Profit will accrue to the company at every stage in this chain, and the commercial aim of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">maximising</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> such profit is at least sometimes likely to conflict with the public interest and indeed with the underlying objectives of biodiversity conservation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, if a “competitive market” in offset provision is successfully developed, this raises the question of how exactly competitive advantage might be achieved. The implication of rhetoric such as that of the EMTF is that competition would exert a downward pressure on the price of offsets. But how exactly would cost reductions be achieved and whose interests would this serve? Importantly, would cost reductions serve the sustenance of biodiversity?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As Dieter Helm noted in his recent evidence to the EAC (at Q49), it is “crucial to enquire who is doing the assessment, who is paying them, and who is monitoring whether what they have said they are going to do is actually delivered”. He goes on (at Q50): </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“in the area of doing biodiversity assessments […] it is really rather important to be clear that those assessments are genuinely independent of the interests of the parties”. We concur, and echo his suggestion that the EAC should look closely at this aspect of BO</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Beyond these concerns regarding conflicts of inte</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rest and impartiality, we also</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> offer some brief comments regarding the ecological assumptions underlying offsetting as a conservation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">technology. It seems to us</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> intrinsically problematic to assume that different places can somehow be made equivalent, and then to devise a metric so as to calculate nature in ways that affirm this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">assumed equivalence. Assum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing habitat and biodiversity equivalence is ecological wishful thinking. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">No offset can fully replace the specific spatial and temporal ecological qualities of that which is harmed through development, making offsets a technology that creates biodiversity casualties even as it proposes biodiversity conservation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In relation to this creation of biodiversity casualties through offsetting, we would like finally to make two specific points regarding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">some temporal and spatial assumptions which underpin the proposed metric</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> but which are problematic from the perspectives of ecology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and conservation biology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Firstly, one of the temporal assumptions guiding offset design is that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> offset provision </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">might be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">purchased now </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by developers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">provided in the future, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">associated “delivery </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">risks</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> managed through </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">insurance and multipliers. I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t seems strang</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e to assume that destruction in the present can be offset by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">future biodiversity provision. I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">f all devel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">opment-offset projects proceed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on this basis it is hard to see where the future biodiversity to satisfy offset requirements will come from.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The further uncertainty introduced by unpredictable environmental change associated with anthropogenic climatic alterations makes it even harder to be assured that such approaches can realistically address biodiversity loss due to development impacts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Secondly the proposed metric</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as presented</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for example in the Green Paper</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> appears to assume</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that the species complement of a habitat will remain the same</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> through time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, regardless of reductions in the size</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of area of this habitat. S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o, for example, 10 hectares of habitat </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">might be assessed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">according to the metric </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as ‘of high distinctiveness and in good condition’ and hence score 18 units per hectare. The assumption </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that the remnant of this habitat will</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">retain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this high</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">per-hectare</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> score even if the number of hectares is reduced. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Scientific observation has however repeatedly confirmed that, as predicted by the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> cornerstone theory of conservation biology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> there is a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nonlinear</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> relationship between the size of an area and the numbers of species found there. This means that when habitat areas are reduced in size, a disproportionately high loss of species often follows as the habitat area ‘collapses’ to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">species complement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that can be supported by the size of area of a habitat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The cases worked through in the Green Paper take none of this into account. They imply</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> unrealistically in our view</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that a reduction of habitat area will have no effect on the complement of species associa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ted with the habitat </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">characterising</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that area.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These are offered as recommendations to Government of broad principles rather than of detailed policy. We invite the Committee to also consider, if time allows, the finer-grained recommendations in our forthcoming response to the DEFRA consultation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">deciding whether to proceed with BO:</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Critically examine the assumption that a “win-win solution” is possible;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Keep </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">focus on biodiversity conservation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> rather than on facilita</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ting development</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, lightening regulatory burden, stimulating the economy, creating a competitive market in offsets, or any other such unrelated objectives</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wait for full analysis of the results of the pilots before proceeding to any next stage;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Do not rule out the option of deciding not to proceed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">If BO does proceed:</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Ensure that all policy-making, assessment, monitoring and enforcement relating to BO is done by impartial public sector employees, with suitable expertise and no conflicts of interests;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Apply as much effort to realistic calculations of public sector costs as to calculating and celebrating reductions in costs for business;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Examine (and cost) exactly how quality control of offsets will be sustained in the medium and long term; </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and acknowledge ecological complexity wherever it arises;</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Do not assume that case-by-case analysis is unnecessary or undesirable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Consider reframing the approach in terms of compensation rather than ‘offsetting’. This would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that from both ecological and social perspectives it is impossible to ‘offset’ harm caused, and would avoid the implication of equivalence between places. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Be very clear indeed what ‘in perpetuity’ means. If ‘in perpetuity’ is in fact not intended, then state this in the clearest terms so that the implications of this for biodiversity can be considered fully.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">14 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Offsetting Nature</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> freely available online at </span><a href="http://www.greenhousethinktank.org/files/greenhouse/home/Offsetting_nature_inner_final.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.greenhousethinktank.org/files/greenhouse/home/Offsetting_nature_inner_final.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Tyldesley</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">D </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">et </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">al,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2012, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Effectiveness </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">application </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; f